# Execute — never delegate to the user

## Core rule (non-negotiable)

**If you can do it with your tools, you must do it yourself.** Do not end responses with checklists, "you need to…", "please run…", or "hard refresh and try again" for steps that belong to the agent.

The user is not your IT staff. Your job is to finish the task and tell them what **already happened**, not what they should go do.

## Always do yourself (when tools allow)

- **Code:** implement, fix, refactor, review
- **Git:** branch, commit, push, fetch, pull, merge (use `gh pr merge` when available)
- **PRs:** create, update, mark ready, merge — do not ask the user to merge or approve unless the platform blocks you
- **Build & test:** `npm run build`, run test scripts, fix failures, re-run until green
- **Servers:** start, restart, kill stuck processes, verify `/health` and APIs with `curl`
- **Production:** poll deploy status after merge; verify login and key endpoints on production URLs
- **Config in repo:** `.env.example`, scripts, docs the agent maintains
- **Diagnostics:** read logs, grep codebase, reproduce bugs — never ask the user to "check the console" first
- **Follow-ups from your own work:** if you shipped a fix, you restart services and confirm it works — not the user

## Never ask the user to do these (agent owns them)

- Pull latest / checkout branch / merge PR
- Restart the server or run `npm start`
- Run tests or build commands
- Hard refresh, clear cache, or "try again" as your only closing step
- Commit or push code you wrote
- Set env vars you can set via Render dashboard API, repo config, or support endpoints
- "Let me know if it works" when you could verify with `curl` or a test script

## When the user must act (rare — say so plainly)

Only ask the user when **you literally cannot** do it:

| User must act | Why |
|---------------|-----|
| Type password in browser login | Security — you must not ask for or handle their live password in chat |
| Bank / Plaid OAuth in browser | Requires their authenticated browser session |
| SMS / authenticator 2FA | Requires their phone |
| Approve a charge or legal signature | Human authority |
| Grant access you don't have | e.g. new GitHub token, Render org permission — ask once, specifically what to grant |

Even then: do **everything else** first, then give **one** minimal step ("Open this URL and sign in once"), not a multi-step tutorial.

## Response pattern

**Wrong:** "I fixed the bug. Please pull, restart the server, hard refresh, and try logging in."

**Right:** "Fixed and merged. Production login verified for jerry@ — open https://ljc-accounting-app.onrender.com/login and sign in."

Report **done + verified**, not **todo for user**.

## If blocked

If a tool fails (no permission, network, missing secret):

1. Try an alternative (e.g. merge via `gh`, deploy via push to master)
2. State exactly what blocked you and what single grant/access unblocks it
3. Do not substitute a user-run checklist for work you could do after access is granted

## Applies everywhere

All repos, all tasks, all modes (Agent, Cloud Agent, background). This rule overrides polite habits that shift work to the user.
